{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486617"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:38:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:38:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"145"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/145"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.42,0.01,0.14,0.39]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"145"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51280"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/145"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"145"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36563"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1914"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1833"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7543"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7677"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8157"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14200"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14560"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43784"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51280"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 33-year-old recent migrant from Tibet presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of subjective fevers and chills, generalised abdominal pain, abdominal distension and leg swelling. He is usually fit and well, and does not take any regular medications. He drinks alcohol socially once a week and up to four standard drinks at a time. He denies any previous intravenous drug use but states that his father had \u0022liver issues\u0022 which he was told he may be also be at risk of developing. Throughout the history the patient appears drowsy and requires redirecting to answer questions appropriately.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.3\u00b0C. His abdomen is uniformly distended, with shifting dullness. There is generalised tenderness with rigidity and rebound tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis blood tests results are shown below. A chest x-ray is clear.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause for the current presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ascending cholangitis","Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis","Acute cholecystitis","Acute hepatitis B infection","Acute flare of chronic hepatitis B"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has presented with clinical decompensation of liver disease with worsening ascites and oedema. The most likely cause of the fever and abdominal pain in someone with chronic liver disease is \u003Cstrong\u003Espontaneous bacterial peritonitis\u003C/strong\u003E. A diagnostic tap ideally should be performed prior to prompt administration of antibiotics. Not uncommonly, antibiotics are started on cirrhotic patients simply based on decompensation and the presence of fever, as significant delays can lead to further deterioration of the patient. If a radiologically guided tap is needed and could delay treatment, antibiotics should be started promptly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute flare of chronic hepatitis B \u003C/strong\u003Eis not the most likely cause for the current presentation. The patient\u0027s hepatitis B serology is suggestive of chronic hepatitis B infection (positive surface antigen, IgM core antibody negative), which is likely the underlying cause of his liver disease. However, chronic viral hepatitis is generally asymptomatic until cirrhosis and decompensation develops, and SBP would be far more likely an explanation for this patient\u0027s fever and abdominal pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAscending cholangitis\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as acute cholangitis, is a serious bacterial infection of the bile ducts. The symptoms of ascending cholangitis can include fever, chills, abdominal pain, jaundice and dark urine. Acute cholangitis presents with upper abdominal pain and tenderness in contrast to the generalised pain and tenderness seen in this patient. People with bile duct obstruction, such as gallstones or tumours, are at increased risk for ascending cholangitis rather than someone with chronic liver disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute cholecystitis,\u003C/strong\u003E inflammation of the gallbladder, presents with severe pain in the upper right side or center of the abdomen, pain that may spread to the right shoulder, fever, nausea and vomiting. The symptoms and signs of this patient (generalised tenderness, distended abdomen and shifting dullness) are not consistent with acute cholecystitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute hepatitis B infection\u003C/strong\u003E is often asymptomatic, but can sometimes lead to symptoms including fatigue, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, and jaundice, rarely resulting in acute liver failure. While some of these symptoms overlap with the patient\u0027s presentation, the presence of ascites would be unusual, and there are no risk factors for acquisition during adulthood presented in the case (e.g. intravenous drug use, unprotected sex) . Additionally, we would expect positive anti-HBc IgM in acute infection. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fever and abdominal pain in a patient with liver disease and ascites must raise the possibility of spontaneous bacterial peritonitis."],"references":["Dever JB, Sheikh MY. Review article: spontaneous bacterial peritonitis \u2013 bacteriology, diagnosis, treatment, risk factors and prevention. Aliment Pharmacol Ther 2015; 41:1116-31.","Chang, M. L., \u0026 Liaw, Y. F. (2014). Hepatitis B flares in chronic hepatitis B: pathogenesis, natural course, and management. Journal of hepatology, 61(6), 1407\u20131417. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jhep.2014.08.033"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36563"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"145"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19945"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19945"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7f3b3c8d-4a54-40de-9c64-a900bf76e902.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7f3b3c8d-4a54-40de-9c64-a900bf76e902.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":963,"height":705}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36563"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-23T11:55:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-23T11:56:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"145"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51280"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji"